e-from the pampering of white middle class women to the artistic self-expression of working class African American women to the mass consumption of body-related services. Contrary to notions of beauty service establishments as spaces for building community among women, The Managed Hand finds that while tentative and fragile solidarities can emerge across the manicure table, they generally give way to even more powerful divisions of race, class, and immigration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAsian AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aBeauty culturexSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aKorean American womenxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aWomen immigrantsxEmploymentzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aafrican american women.  aart.  aasian american.  aasian immigrants.  aasian women.  abeauty service work.  abody services.  abody.  aclass differences.  aconsumption.  adivisions of race.  aethnography.  agender issues.  agender.  aimmigrant workers.  ainterviews.  akorean women.  amanicures.  anail industry.  anail salons.  anew york city.  anonfiction.  apampering.  arace issues.  aself care.  aself expression.  aservice careers.  asocial science.  aunited states.  awhite middle class women.  awomen.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026258440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094565440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945654/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY